[0m[49m[39m  176, 176[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  177, 177[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  178, 178[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  179, 179[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  180, 180[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  181, 181[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon Kinesis Data Streams, AWS Lambda, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon EventBridge, Amazon CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[39m  182, 182[0m:[39m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `kinesis:GetRecords`, `kinesis:PutRecord`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:UpdateItem`, `events:PutRule`, `events:PutTargets`. Note: these represent the aggregate across all components. Each Lambda function should have a dedicated execution role scoped to only the permissions it needs (e.g., the scoring Lambda needs `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint` and `dynamodb:GetItem/PutItem` but not `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob` or `glue:StartJobRun`). |
[0m[49m[39m  183, 183[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (required: all patient clinical data is PHI) |
[0m[49m[39m  184, 184[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); Kinesis: server-side encryption with KMS (24-hour retention, minimum sufficient for this use case); SageMaker: KMS for training volumes and model artifacts; all API calls over TLS |
[0m[49m[39m  185, 185[0m:[39m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker training and endpoints in VPC (enable `EnableNetworkIsolation=True` on inference endpoints to prevent outbound calls from model containers); Lambda in VPC with endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker Runtime, Kinesis, CloudWatch Logs, KMS, STS, and EventBridge; VPC Flow Logs enabled |
[0m[49m[39m  186, 186[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all SageMaker, S3, DynamoDB, Kinesis, and Lambda API calls for HIPAA audit trail. Set CloudWatch Logs retention policy (e.g., 90 days) rather than indefinite retention. |
[0m[49m[39m  187, 187[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic longitudinal patient data with timestamped events. MIMIC-IV provides realistic ICU timelines. CMS Synthetic Public Use Files provide claims-level longitudinal data. Never use real PHI in development. |
[0m[49m[39m  188, 188[0m:[39m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | SageMaker training: ~$500-2,000/run (GPU instances, depends on data volume). SageMaker endpoint: ~$800-3,000/month (ml.m5.xlarge or larger). Kinesis: ~$50-200/month. Glue: ~$100-500/month. DynamoDB: ~$50-200/month. VPC endpoints and data transfer: ~$50-150/month. Lambda: negligible. |
[0m[49m[39m  189, 189[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  190, 190[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  191, 191[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  192, 192[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  193, 193[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  194, 194[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Trains dynamic survival model on longitudinal patient data; hosts real-time inference endpoint |
[0m[49m[39m  195, 195[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores patient timeline datasets, model artifacts, and training outputs |
[0m[49m[39m  196, 196[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Glue** | Assembles patient timelines from disparate source systems; runs incremental daily updates |
[0m[49m[39m  197, 197[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams** | Ingests real-time clinical events (ADT, labs, medication fills) for immediate scoring |
[0m[49m[39m  198, 198[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Applies intervention window decision logic to model predictions; generates recommendations |
[0m[49m[39m  199, 199[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores current patient state, risk trajectories, and intervention recommendations |
[0m[49m[39m  200, 200[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Orchestrates batch retraining, daily feature updates, and real-time scoring triggers |
[0m[49m[39m  201, 201[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitors model latency, prediction drift, scoring throughput, and alerting |
[0m[49m[39m  202, 202[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for all data stores and model artifacts |
[0m[49m[39m  203, 203[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  204, 204[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  205, 205[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  206, 206[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  207, 207[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  208, 208[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Assemble patient timelines.** The foundation of any timing model is a complete, time-ordered sequence of clinical events for each patient. This step pulls data from multiple source systems (EHR, claims, pharmacy, labs) and aligns everything on a unified timeline. Each event gets a timestamp, an event type, and relevant attributes. The output is one record per patient containing their full event history, sorted chronologically. This is the hardest engineering step in the entire pipeline. Healthcare data is fragmented across systems with different identifiers, different time zones, and different update frequencies. Getting this right is 60% of the work. Skip this step or do it poorly, and your model trains on incomplete or misaligned data, producing timing predictions that are systematically wrong.
[0m[49m[39m  209, 209[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  210, 210[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  211, 211[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION assemble_patient_timeline(patient_id, lookback_days=730):
[0m[49m[39m  212, 212[0m:[39m[49m     // Pull events from each source system for this patient.
[0m[49m[39m  213, 213[0m:[39m[49m     // lookback_days controls how far back we look (2 years is typical for chronic conditions).
[0m[49m[39m  214, 214[0m:[39m[49m     // Each source returns events in its own format; we normalize to a common schema.
[0m[49m[39m  215, 215[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  216, 216[0m:[39m[49m     encounters   = query EHR for encounters where patient = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  217, 217[0m:[39m[49m                    AND date >= (today - lookback_days)
[0m[49m[39m  218, 218[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  219, 219[0m:[39m[49m     claims       = query claims warehouse for claims where member_id = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  220, 220[0m:[39m[49m                    AND service_date >= (today - lookback_days)
[0m[49m[39m  221, 221[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  222, 222[0m:[39m[49m     medications  = query pharmacy system for fills where patient = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  223, 223[0m:[39m[49m                    AND fill_date >= (today - lookback_days)
[0m[49m[39m  224, 224[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  225, 225[0m:[39m[49m     labs         = query lab system for results where patient = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  226, 226[0m:[39m[49m                    AND result_date >= (today - lookback_days)
[0m[49m[39m  227, 227[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  228, 228[0m:[39m[49m     vitals       = query EHR for vital signs where patient = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  229, 229[0m:[39m[49m                    AND measurement_date >= (today - lookback_days)
[0m[49m[39m  230, 230[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  231, 231[0m:[39m[49m     // Normalize each event to a common schema:
[0m[49m[39m  232, 232[0m:[39m[49m     // { timestamp, event_type, event_subtype, attributes: {} }
[0m[49m[39m  233, 233[0m:[39m[49m     all_events = []
[0m[49m[39m  234, 234[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  235, 235[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each encounter in encounters:
[0m[49m[39m  236, 236[0m:[39m[49m         append to all_events: {
[0m[49m[39m  237, 237[0m:[39m[49m             timestamp:    encounter.date,
[0m[49m[39m  238, 238[0m:[39m[49m             event_type:   "encounter",
[0m[49m[39m  239, 239[0m:[39m[49m             event_subtype: encounter.type,       // "inpatient", "outpatient", "ED", "telehealth"
[0m[49m[39m  240, 240[0m:[39m[49m             attributes: {
[0m[49m[39m  241, 241[0m:[39m[49m                 diagnosis_codes: encounter.diagnoses,
[0m[49m[39m  242, 242[0m:[39m[49m                 provider_type:   encounter.provider_specialty,
[0m[49m[39m  243, 243[0m:[39m[49m                 length_of_stay:  encounter.los_days    // null for outpatient
[0m[49m[39m  244, 244[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  245, 245[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  246, 246[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  247, 247[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each claim in claims:
[0m[49m[39m  248, 248[0m:[39m[49m         append to all_events: {
[0m[49m[39m  249, 249[0m:[39m[49m             timestamp:    claim.service_date,
[0m[49m[39m  250, 250[0m:[39m[49m             event_type:   "claim",
[0m[49m[39m  251, 251[0m:[39m[49m             event_subtype: claim.claim_type,     // "professional", "facility", "pharmacy"
[0m[49m[39m  252, 252[0m:[39m[49m             attributes: {
[0m[49m[39m  253, 253[0m:[39m[49m                 procedure_codes: claim.procedures,
[0m[49m[39m  254, 254[0m:[39m[49m                 total_charge:    claim.billed_amount
[0m[49m[39m  255, 255[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  256, 256[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  257, 257[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  258, 258[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each med in medications:
[0m[49m[39m  259, 259[0m:[39m[49m         append to all_events: {
[0m[49m[39m  260, 260[0m:[39m[49m             timestamp:    med.fill_date,
[0m[49m[39m  261, 261[0m:[39m[49m             event_type:   "medication",
[0m[49m[39m  262, 262[0m:[39m[49m             event_subtype: "fill",
[0m[49m[39m  263, 263[0m:[39m[49m             attributes: {
[0m[49m[39m  264, 264[0m:[39m[49m                 drug_name:    med.drug_name,
[0m[49m[39m  265, 265[0m:[39m[49m                 days_supply:  med.days_supply,
[0m[49m[39m  266, 266[0m:[39m[49m                 refill_number: med.refill_num
[0m[49m[39m  267, 267[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  268, 268[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  269, 269[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  270, 270[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each lab in labs:
[0m[49m[39m  271, 271[0m:[39m[49m         append to all_events: {
[0m[49m[39m  272, 272[0m:[39m[49m             timestamp:    lab.result_date,
[0m[49m[39m  273, 273[0m:[39m[49m             event_type:   "lab",
[0m[49m[39m  274, 274[0m:[39m[49m             event_subtype: lab.test_code,
[0m[49m[39m  275, 275[0m:[39m[49m             attributes: {
[0m[49m[39m  276, 276[0m:[39m[49m                 value:          lab.result_value,
[0m[49m[39m  277, 277[0m:[39m[49m                 reference_low:  lab.ref_range_low,
[0m[49m[39m  278, 278[0m:[39m[49m                 reference_high: lab.ref_range_high,
[0m[49m[39m  279, 279[0m:[39m[49m                 abnormal_flag:  lab.abnormal_flag
[0m[49m[39m  280, 280[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  281, 281[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  282, 282[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  283, 283[0m:[39m[49m     // Sort all events chronologically. This ordering is critical:
[0m[49m[39m  284, 284[0m:[39m[49m     // the model learns from the sequence, not just the values.
[0m[49m[39m  285, 285[0m:[39m[49m     sort all_events by timestamp ascending
[0m[49m[39m  286, 286[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  287, 287[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  288, 288[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id: patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  289, 289[0m:[39m[49m         timeline:   all_events,
[0m[49m[39m  290, 290[0m:[39m[49m         event_count: length of all_events,
[0m[49m[39m  291, 291[0m:[39m[49m         span_days:   (latest timestamp - earliest timestamp) in days
[0m[49m[39m  292, 292[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  293, 293[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  294, 294[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  295, 295[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Engineer temporal features.** Raw events aren't directly useful for a timing model. You need features that capture temporal dynamics: how fast things are changing, how long since key events occurred, whether patterns are accelerating or decelerating. This step transforms the raw timeline into a feature vector at each time step, creating the input the survival model needs. The features here are specifically designed to capture inflection points, not just current state. A patient whose A1C has been 8.5 for two years is different from a patient whose A1C just jumped from 7.0 to 8.5 in one quarter, even though their current value is similar. Skip this step and feed raw events directly to the model, and it will struggle to learn timing patterns because the signal is buried in noise.
[0m[49m[39m  296, 296[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  297, 297[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  298, 298[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION engineer_temporal_features(timeline, observation_date):
[0m[49m[39m  299, 299[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute features that capture the temporal dynamics at a specific observation point.
[0m[49m[39m  300, 300[0m:[39m[49m     // These features are computed for each "time step" during training,
[0m[49m[39m  301, 301[0m:[39m[49m     // and for the current date during inference.
[0m[49m[39m  302, 302[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  303, 303[0m:[39m[49m     features = {}
[0m[49m[39m  304, 304[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  305, 305[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Recency features: how long since key events ---
[0m[49m[39m  306, 306[0m:[39m[49m     features["days_since_last_encounter"]    = days between observation_date
[0m[49m[39m  307, 307[0m:[39m[49m                                                and most recent encounter in timeline
[0m[49m[39m  308, 308[0m:[39m[49m     features["days_since_last_ed_visit"]     = days between observation_date
[0m[49m[39m  309, 309[0m:[39m[49m                                                and most recent ED encounter (null if none)
[0m[49m[39m  310, 310[0m:[39m[49m     features["days_since_last_inpatient"]    = days between observation_date
[0m[49m[39m  311, 311[0m:[39m[49m                                                and most recent inpatient stay (null if none)
[0m[49m[39m  312, 312[0m:[39m[49m     features["days_since_last_med_fill"]     = days between observation_date
[0m[49m[39m  313, 313[0m:[39m[49m                                                and most recent medication fill
[0m[49m[39m  314, 314[0m:[39m[49m     features["days_since_last_lab"]          = days between observation_date
[0m[49m[39m  315, 315[0m:[39m[49m                                                and most recent lab result
[0m[49m[39m  316, 316[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  317, 317[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Velocity features: rate of change ---
[0m[49m[39m  318, 318[0m:[39m[49m     // For key lab values, compute the slope over the last 90 days.
[0m[49m[39m  319, 319[0m:[39m[49m     // A rising A1C slope signals deteriorating glycemic control.
[0m[49m[39m  320, 320[0m:[39m[49m     a1c_values = extract lab values where test_code = "A1C"
[0m[49m[39m  321, 321[0m:[39m[49m                  AND timestamp within (observation_date - 365, observation_date)
[0m[49m[39m  322, 322[0m:[39m[49m     IF length of a1c_values >= 2:
[0m[49m[39m  323, 323[0m:[39m[49m         features["a1c_slope_90d"] = linear regression slope of a1c_values
[0m[49m[39m  324, 324[0m:[39m[49m                                     over last 90 days
[0m[49m[39m  325, 325[0m:[39m[49m         features["a1c_current"]   = most recent a1c value
[0m[49m[39m  326, 326[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  327, 327[0m:[39m[49m         features["a1c_slope_90d"] = null
[0m[49m[39m  328, 328[0m:[39m[49m         features["a1c_current"]   = null
[0m[49m[39m  329, 329[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  330, 330[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Acceleration features: is the rate of change itself changing? ---
[0m[49m[39m  331, 331[0m:[39m[49m     // Compare recent utilization rate to historical baseline.
[0m[49m[39m  332, 332[0m:[39m[49m     encounters_last_30d  = count encounters in (observation_date - 30, observation_date)
[0m[49m[39m  333, 333[0m:[39m[49m     encounters_prior_30d = count encounters in (observation_date - 60, observation_date - 30)
[0m[49m[39m  334, 334[0m:[39m[49m     features["encounter_acceleration"] = encounters_last_30d - encounters_prior_30d
[0m[49m[39m  335, 335[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  336, 336[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Gap features: missed expected events ---
[0m[49m[39m  337, 337[0m:[39m[49m     // If a patient has a 90-day medication supply and hasn't refilled in 100 days,
[0m[49m[39m  338, 338[0m:[39m[49m     // that gap is a strong timing signal.
[0m[49m[39m  339, 339[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each active medication:
[0m[49m[39m  340, 340[0m:[39m[49m         expected_refill_date = last_fill_date + days_supply
[0m[49m[39m  341, 341[0m:[39m[49m         IF observation_date > expected_refill_date:
[0m[49m[39m  342, 342[0m:[39m[49m             features["med_gap_days_" + drug_class] = observation_date - expected_refill_date
[0m[49m[39m  343, 343[0m:[39m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  344, 344[0m:[39m[49m             features["med_gap_days_" + drug_class] = 0
[0m[49m[39m  345, 345[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  346, 346[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Pattern features: behavioral signals ---
[0m[49m[39m  347, 347[0m:[39m[49m     features["missed_appointments_90d"]  = count of no-shows in last 90 days
[0m[49m[39m  348, 348[0m:[39m[49m     features["cancelled_appointments_90d"] = count of cancellations in last 90 days
[0m[49m[39m  349, 349[0m:[39m[49m     features["total_encounters_180d"]    = count of all encounters in last 180 days
[0m[49m[39m  350, 350[0m:[39m[49m     features["ed_visits_365d"]           = count of ED visits in last 365 days
[0m[49m[39m  351, 351[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  352, 352[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Intervention history: when was the patient last contacted? ---
[0m[49m[39m  353, 353[0m:[39m[49m     features["days_since_last_intervention"] = days since last care management outreach
[0m[49m[39m  354, 354[0m:[39m[49m     features["interventions_90d"]            = count of interventions in last 90 days
[0m[49m[39m  355, 355[0m:[39m[49m     features["last_intervention_outcome"]    = outcome of most recent intervention
[0m[49m[39m  356, 356[0m:[39m[49m                                                // "engaged", "no_answer", "declined"
[0m[49m[39m  357, 357[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  358, 358[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN features
[0m[49m[39m  359, 359[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  360, 360[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  361, 361[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Train the dynamic survival model.** This is where the temporal features become a timing prediction. The model learns, from historical patient trajectories and their outcomes, to estimate the hazard function at each time step. During training, it sees thousands of patient timelines with known event times and learns which feature patterns precede events, and crucially, how far in advance those patterns appear. The output is a model that can take any patient's current feature vector and predict their hazard trajectory over the next N days. This trajectory is what enables timing decisions: a flat trajectory means "no urgency," a rising trajectory means "window is opening," and a peaked trajectory means "window may be closing."
[0m[49m[39m  362, 362[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  363, 363[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  364, 364[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION train_survival_model(training_data):
[0m[49m[39m  365, 365[0m:[39m[49m     // training_data contains:
[0m[49m[39m  366, 366[0m:[39m[49m     //   - patient timelines (feature sequences)
[0m[49m[39m  367, 367[0m:[39m[49m     //   - event indicators (did the patient have the target event?)
[0m[49m[39m  368, 368[0m:[39m[49m     //   - event times (when did it happen, relative to each observation point?)
[0m[49m[39m  369, 369[0m:[39m[49m     //   - censoring indicators (did we lose track of the patient before observing an event?)
[0m[49m[39m  370, 370[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  371, 371[0m:[39m[49m     // Define model architecture: LSTM-based survival network.
[0m[49m[39m  372, 372[0m:[39m[49m     // The LSTM processes the feature sequence and outputs a hazard estimate at each step.
[0m[49m[39m  373, 373[0m:[39m[49m     model = create LSTM survival network with:
[0m[49m[39m  374, 374[0m:[39m[49m         input_dim    = number of temporal features
[0m[49m[39m  375, 375[0m:[39m[49m         hidden_dim   = 128                    // capacity to learn complex temporal patterns
[0m[49m[39m  376, 376[0m:[39m[49m         num_layers   = 2                      // depth for capturing hierarchical patterns
[0m[49m[39m  377, 377[0m:[39m[49m         output_dim   = forecast_horizon_days  // predict hazard for each of the next N days
[0m[49m[39m  378, 378[0m:[39m[49m         dropout      = 0.3                    // regularization to prevent overfitting
[0m[49m[39m  379, 379[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  380, 380[0m:[39m[49m     // Loss function: negative log-likelihood of the observed survival times.
[0m[49m[39m  381, 381[0m:[39m[49m     // This is the standard survival analysis loss that handles censored observations
[0m[49m[39m  382, 382[0m:[39m[49m     // (patients who didn't have an event during the observation window).
[0m[49m[39m  383, 383[0m:[39m[49m     loss_function = negative_log_partial_likelihood
[0m[49m[39m  384, 384[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  385, 385[0m:[39m[49m     // Training loop
[0m[49m[39m  386, 386[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each epoch in 1..100:
[0m[49m[39m  387, 387[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each batch of patient sequences:
[0m[49m[39m  388, 388[0m:[39m[49m             // Forward pass: model predicts hazard at each time step
[0m[49m[39m  389, 389[0m:[39m[49m             predicted_hazards = model(batch.feature_sequences)
[0m[49m[39m  390, 390[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  391, 391[0m:[39m[49m             // Compute loss against actual event times
[0m[49m[39m  392, 392[0m:[39m[49m             loss = loss_function(predicted_hazards, batch.event_times,
[0m[49m[39m  393, 393[0m:[39m[49m                                  batch.event_indicators, batch.censoring_indicators)
[0m[49m[39m  394, 394[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  395, 395[0m:[39m[49m             // Backward pass: update model weights
[0m[49m[39m  396, 396[0m:[39m[49m             update model weights using loss gradient
[0m[49m[39m  397, 397[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  398, 398[0m:[39m[49m         // Evaluate on validation set: concordance index (C-index)
[0m[49m[39m  399, 399[0m:[39m[49m         // C-index measures whether patients with higher predicted hazard
[0m[49m[39m  400, 400[0m:[39m[49m         // actually have events sooner. 0.5 = random, 1.0 = perfect.
[0m[49m[39m  401, 401[0m:[39m[49m         c_index = evaluate concordance on validation_set
[0m[49m[39m  402, 402[0m:[39m[49m         log("Epoch {epoch}: C-index = {c_index}")
[0m[49m[39m  403, 403[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  404, 404[0m:[39m[49m         // Early stopping if validation performance plateaus
[0m[49m[39m  405, 405[0m:[39m[49m         IF c_index has not improved for 10 epochs:
[0m[49m[39m  406, 406[0m:[39m[49m             BREAK
[0m[49m[39m  407, 407[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  408, 408[0m:[39m[49m     // Save trained model for deployment
[0m[49m[39m  409, 409[0m:[39m[49m     save model to model_registry with:
[0m[49m[39m  410, 410[0m:[39m[49m         version    = current timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  411, 411[0m:[39m[49m         c_index    = best validation c_index
[0m[49m[39m  412, 412[0m:[39m[49m         features   = list of input feature names
[0m[49m[39m  413, 413[0m:[39m[49m         horizon    = forecast_horizon_days
[0m[49m[39m  414, 414[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  415, 415[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN model
[0m[49m[39m  416, 416[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  417, 417[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  418, 418[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Score intervention windows.** This is the decision layer. Given a patient's predicted hazard trajectory, determine whether now is the right time to intervene. The logic encodes clinical beliefs about intervention effectiveness: interventions work best when risk is rising but hasn't peaked (the patient is deteriorating but hasn't yet reached crisis). Too early and the intervention is premature; too late and it's reactive rather than preventive. The scoring function produces an "intervention urgency" score and a recommended action window (e.g., "intervene within the next 3-5 days"). Skip this step and you're back to static risk scoring: you know who's at risk but not when to act.
[0m[49m[39m  419, 419[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  420, 420[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  421, 421[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION score_intervention_window(patient_id, hazard_trajectory):
[0m[49m[39m  422, 422[0m:[39m[49m     // hazard_trajectory is an array of predicted daily hazard values
[0m[49m[39m  423, 423[0m:[39m[49m     // for the next N days (e.g., 30 days).
[0m[49m[39m  424, 424[0m:[39m[49m     // Each value represents the probability of the target event on that specific day,
[0m[49m[39m  425, 425[0m:[39m[49m     // given survival to that day.
[0m[49m[39m  426, 426[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  427, 427[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute trajectory characteristics
[0m[49m[39m  428, 428[0m:[39m[49m     current_hazard     = hazard_trajectory[0]           // today's hazard
[0m[49m[39m  429, 429[0m:[39m[49m     peak_hazard        = maximum value in hazard_trajectory
[0m[49m[39m  430, 430[0m:[39m[49m     peak_day           = index of peak_hazard           // which day the peak occurs
[0m[49m[39m  431, 431[0m:[39m[49m     hazard_slope       = slope of hazard_trajectory over first 7 days
[0m[49m[39m  432, 432[0m:[39m[49m     hazard_acceleration = second derivative of trajectory over first 14 days
[0m[49m[39m  433, 433[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  434, 434[0m:[39m[49m     // Retrieve patient's intervention history
[0m[49m[39m  435, 435[0m:[39m[49m     patient_state = lookup patient_id in patient state store
[0m[49m[39m  436, 436[0m:[39m[49m     days_since_last_intervention = today - patient_state.last_intervention_date
[0m[49m[39m  437, 437[0m:[39m[49m     recent_intervention_outcome  = patient_state.last_intervention_outcome
[0m[49m[39m  438, 438[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  439, 439[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Decision logic ---
[0m[49m[39m  440, 440[0m:[39m[49m     // The intervention window is optimal when:
[0m[49m[39m  441, 441[0m:[39m[49m     // 1. Risk is rising (positive slope) - the patient is deteriorating
[0m[49m[39m  442, 442[0m:[39m[49m     // 2. Peak is still ahead (not behind us) - we haven't missed the window
[0m[49m[39m  443, 443[0m:[39m[49m     // 3. Enough time since last intervention - avoid outreach fatigue
[0m[49m[39m  444, 444[0m:[39m[49m     // 4. Previous intervention wasn't recently declined - respect patient preferences
[0m[49m[39m  445, 445[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  446, 446[0m:[39m[49m     intervention_score = 0.0
[0m[49m[39m  447, 447[0m:[39m[49m     recommended_action = "monitor"
[0m[49m[39m  448, 448[0m:[39m[49m     action_window_days = null
[0m[49m[39m  449, 449[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  450, 450[0m:[39m[49m     // Rising risk with peak ahead: prime intervention window
[0m[49m[39m  451, 451[0m:[39m[49m     IF hazard_slope > 0.01 AND peak_day > 2 AND peak_day < 14:
[0m[49m[39m  452, 452[0m:[39m[49m         intervention_score = hazard_slope * 100 * (peak_hazard / current_hazard)
[0m[49m[39m  453, 453[0m:[39m[49m         // Scale by how much worse it's going to get (peak/current ratio)
[0m[49m[39m  454, 454[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  455, 455[0m:[39m[49m     // Already at or past peak: window may be closing
[0m[49m[39m  456, 456[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF peak_day <= 2 AND current_hazard > HIGH_RISK_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[39m  457, 457[0m:[39m[49m         intervention_score = current_hazard * 50  // urgent but possibly too late
[0m[49m[39m  458, 458[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_action = "urgent_outreach"
[0m[49m[39m  459, 459[0m:[39m[49m         action_window_days = 1
[0m[49m[39m  460, 460[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  461, 461[0m:[39m[49m     // Flat high risk: chronic elevation, timing is less critical
[0m[49m[39m  462, 462[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF current_hazard > MODERATE_RISK_THRESHOLD AND hazard_slope < 0.005:
[0m[49m[39m  463, 463[0m:[39m[49m         intervention_score = current_hazard * 20  // important but not time-sensitive
[0m[49m[39m  464, 464[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_action = "scheduled_outreach"
[0m[49m[39m  465, 465[0m:[39m[49m         action_window_days = 7
[0m[49m[39m  466, 466[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  467, 467[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply intervention fatigue dampening
[0m[49m[39m  468, 468[0m:[39m[49m     IF days_since_last_intervention < 14:
[0m[49m[39m  469, 469[0m:[39m[49m         intervention_score = intervention_score * 0.3  // reduce urgency if recently contacted
[0m[49m[39m  470, 470[0m:[39m[49m     IF recent_intervention_outcome == "declined":
[0m[49m[39m  471, 471[0m:[39m[49m         intervention_score = intervention_score * 0.1  // strongly reduce if patient declined
[0m[49m[39m  472, 472[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  473, 473[0m:[39m[49m     // Determine recommended action based on final score
[0m[49m[39m  474, 474[0m:[39m[49m     IF intervention_score > URGENT_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[39m  475, 475[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_action = "immediate_outreach"
[0m[49m[39m  476, 476[0m:[39m[49m         action_window_days = 2
[0m[49m[39m  477, 477[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF intervention_score > ACTION_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[39m  478, 478[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_action = "outreach_this_week"
[0m[49m[39m  479, 479[0m:[39m[49m         action_window_days = peak_day - 1  // intervene before the predicted peak
[0m[49m[39m  480, 480[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  481, 481[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  482, 482[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id:          patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  483, 483[0m:[39m[49m         intervention_score:  intervention_score,
[0m[49m[39m  484, 484[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_action:  recommended_action,
[0m[49m[39m  485, 485[0m:[39m[49m         action_window_days:  action_window_days,
[0m[49m[39m  486, 486[0m:[39m[49m         current_hazard:      current_hazard,
[0m[49m[39m  487, 487[0m:[39m[49m         predicted_peak_day:  peak_day,
[0m[49m[39m  488, 488[0m:[39m[49m         peak_hazard:         peak_hazard,
[0m[49m[39m  489, 489[0m:[39m[49m         trajectory_slope:    hazard_slope,
[0m[49m[39m  490, 490[0m:[39m[49m         scored_at:           current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  491, 491[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  492, 492[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  493, 493[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  494, 494[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Generate and deliver recommendations.** The final step assembles the scored patients into an actionable worklist for the care team. It applies operational constraints (care manager capacity, patient contact preferences, time of day), ranks patients by intervention urgency, and writes the recommendations to the delivery layer. The "why now" explanation is critical: care managers won't act on a score without understanding what changed. This step generates a human-readable explanation of why this patient, why today. Skip this step and you have a model that produces numbers but doesn't change behavior.
[0m[49m[39m  495, 495[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  496, 496[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  497, 497[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION generate_recommendations(scored_patients, care_team_capacity):
[0m[49m[39m  498, 498[0m:[39m[49m     // scored_patients: list of intervention window scores from Step 4
[0m[49m[39m  499, 499[0m:[39m[49m     // care_team_capacity: how many outreach slots are available today
[0m[49m[39m  500, 500[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  501, 501[0m:[39m[49m     // Filter to actionable recommendations only
[0m[49m[39m  502, 502[0m:[39m[49m     actionable = filter scored_patients where recommended_action != "monitor"
[0m[49m[39m  503, 503[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  504, 504[0m:[39m[49m     // Sort by intervention score descending (most urgent first)
[0m[49m[39m  505, 505[0m:[39m[49m     sort actionable by intervention_score descending
[0m[49m[39m  506, 506[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  507, 507[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply capacity constraint: only recommend what the team can handle
[0m[49m[39m  508, 508[0m:[39m[49m     recommendations = take first care_team_capacity items from actionable
[0m[49m[39m  509, 509[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  510, 510[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each rec in recommendations:
[0m[49m[39m  511, 511[0m:[39m[49m         // Generate "why now" explanation for the care manager
[0m[49m[39m  512, 512[0m:[39m[49m         explanation = generate_explanation(rec)
[0m[49m[39m  513, 513[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  514, 514[0m:[39m[49m         // Write recommendation to patient state store
[0m[49m[39m  515, 515[0m:[39m[49m         write to patient state store:
[0m[49m[39m  516, 516[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id:         rec.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  517, 517[0m:[39m[49m             recommendation:     rec.recommended_action,
[0m[49m[39m  518, 518[0m:[39m[49m             urgency_score:      rec.intervention_score,
[0m[49m[39m  519, 519[0m:[39m[49m             action_window:      rec.action_window_days,
[0m[49m[39m  520, 520[0m:[39m[49m             explanation:        explanation,
[0m[49m[39m  521, 521[0m:[39m[49m             generated_at:       current UTC timestamp,
[0m[49m[39m  522, 522[0m:[39m[49m             expires_at:         current timestamp + (rec.action_window_days * 24 hours),
[0m[49m[39m  523, 523[0m:[39m[49m             status:             "pending"    // care manager hasn't acted yet
[0m[49m[39m  524, 524[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  525, 525[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN recommendations
[0m[49m[39m  526, 526[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  527, 527[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  528, 528[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION generate_explanation(scored_result):
[0m[49m[39m  529, 529[0m:[39m[49m     // Build a human-readable explanation of why this patient needs outreach now.
[0m[49m[39m  530, 530[0m:[39m[49m     // Care managers need to understand the "why" to trust and act on the recommendation.
[0m[49m[39m  531, 531[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  532, 532[0m:[39m[49m     parts = []
[0m[49m[39m  533, 533[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  534, 534[0m:[39m[49m     IF scored_result.trajectory_slope > 0.02:
[0m[49m[39m  535, 535[0m:[39m[49m         append to parts: "Risk trajectory is rising sharply"
[0m[49m[39m  536, 536[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  537, 537[0m:[39m[49m     IF scored_result.predicted_peak_day < 7:
[0m[49m[39m  538, 538[0m:[39m[49m         append to parts: "Predicted risk peak within {peak_day} days"
[0m[49m[39m  539, 539[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  540, 540[0m:[39m[49m     IF scored_result.current_hazard > HIGH_RISK_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[39m  541, 541[0m:[39m[49m         append to parts: "Current risk level is elevated"
[0m[49m[39m  542, 542[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  543, 543[0m:[39m[49m     // Add the specific clinical drivers (from the feature importance)
[0m[49m[39m  544, 544[0m:[39m[49m     // These come from the model's attention weights or SHAP values
[0m[49m[39m  545, 545[0m:[39m[49m     top_drivers = get top 3 feature contributors for this patient
[0m[49m[39m  546, 546[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each driver in top_drivers:
[0m[49m[39m  547, 547[0m:[39m[49m         append to parts: driver.description
[0m[49m[39m  548, 548[0m:[39m[49m         // e.g., "A1C increased from 7.8 to 9.1 over last 90 days"
[0m[49m[39m  549, 549[0m:[39m[49m         // e.g., "Missed medication refill (12 days overdue)"
[0m[49m[39m  550, 550[0m:[39m[49m         // e.g., "No PCP visit in 180 days"
[0m[49m[39m  551, 551[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  552, 552[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN join parts with ". "
[0m[49m[39m  553, 553[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  554, 554[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  555, 555[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter07.10-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  556, 556[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  557, 557[0m:[39m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[39m  558, 558[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  559, 559[0m:[39m[49m **Sample output for a diabetes care management panel:**
[0m[49m[39m  560, 560[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  561, 561[0m:[39m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[39m  562, 562[0m:[39m[49m {
